docs\research\2026-04-12-school-role-research.md:172:**Platform gap identified**: edu-cloud currently has NO dedicated `teaching_research_leader` role. The closest is `subject_teacher`, but that is scoped to specific classes. A TRG leader needs **cross-grade, single-subject** access -- the UserRole model supports this via `subject_codes` (restricted) + `grade_ids` (null = all grades) + `class_ids` (null = all classes).
docs\research\2026-04-12-school-role-research.md:295:**Platform mapping**: `homeroom_teacher` -- the current implementation correctly unions homeroom class_ids with teaching assignment class_ids in DataScopeBuilder. However, the key distinction is that for their homeroom class they see ALL subjects, while for their teaching assignments they only see their own subject.
docs\research\2026-04-12-school-role-research.md:297:**Important nuance for the platform**: The DataScope currently tracks `visible_class_ids` and `visible_subject_codes` as flat lists. For a homeroom teacher who teaches Math in classes 7-1, 7-2, 7-3 but is homeroom teacher of 7-1:
docs\research\2026-04-12-school-role-research.md:304:homeroom_access: list[str]  # class_ids where all subjects visible
docs\research\2026-04-12-school-role-research.md:443:- Can be modeled with `subject_codes=[single_subject]` + `grade_ids=null` (all grades) + `class_ids=null` (all classes)
docs\research\2026-04-12-school-role-research.md:450:- Or model as a separate role with `grade_ids=[single_grade]` + `subject_codes=[single_subject]` + `class_ids=null`
docs\research\2026-04-12-school-role-research.md:517:This asymmetry is not trivially captured by flat `visible_class_ids` + `visible_subject_codes` lists. The current DataScopeBuilder unions them, which may over-grant access (a homeroom teacher of 7-1 who teaches Math in 7-2 would see all subjects in both classes, when they should only see Math in 7-2).
